 Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is a diagnostic method to view high quality two and three dimensional images of the body.

 However, magnetic resonance imaging systems generate three electromagnetic fields that are used to produce an image.

 These include a static magnetic field, a time varying gradient magnetic field, and a radiofrequency field.

 All three of these fields interact with implanted devices and could create hazards for the device, the patient, or both.

 Due to these issues, currently marketed pacemaker systems may be contraindicated for use in an MRI environment.

